no-throw-literal.description:
Description

This rule is aimed at maintaining consistency when throwing exception by disallowing to throw literals and other expressions which cannot possibly be anErrorobject.

Examples ofincorrectcode for this rule:

/*eslint no-throw-literal: "error"*/

throw "error";

throw 0;

throw undefined;

throw null;

const err = new Error();
throw "an " + err;
// err is recast to a string literal

const er2 = new Error();
throw `${err2}`

Examples ofcorrectcode for this rule:

/*eslint no-throw-literal: "error"*/

throw new Error();

throw new Error("error");

const e = new Error("error");
throw e;

try {
    throw new Error("error");
} catch (e) {
    throw e;
}
